  "prompt": "What is \u2018double diameter\u2019 in a circle?",
  "response": "In the context of a circle, the term **\"double diameter\"** refers to a length that is exactly twice the length of the circle's diameter. Here's a breakdown:\n\n1. **Diameter (d)**: The diameter of a circle is the straight line passing through the center of the circle, connecting two points on its circumference. It is the longest chord in a circle.\n\n   \\[\n   d = 2r\n   \\]\n   \n   where \\( r \\) is the radius of the circle.\n\n2. **Double Diameter**: This is simply twice the diameter.\n\n   \\[\n   \\text{Double Diameter} = 2 \\times d = 2 \\times (2r) = 4r\n   \\]\n\nSo, the double diameter is equal to four times the radius of the circle.\n\n### Summary\n\n\\[\n\\boxed{4r}\n\\]",
